Invitation to Coding

Code 50

December 2024

1 Introduction

Todays presentation is for Wardroom and NAVMAC members who are brand new to the idea of coding. At the end of the day, you should:

  • Have R installed, and know how to start and end R sessions,
  • Be able to download and call R libraries,
  • Be able to execute lines of code,
  • Be familiar with vectors and data frames in R,
  • Have some exposure to aspects of programming in R, ready for further exploration.

1.1 Why Code?

Coding is the essential skill of the 20th century. The skill of coding acts as a force multiplier in your work, allowing one to tackle large and repetitive tasks, improve and standardize final products, and encourage analytical and consistent thinking.

Coding is more than just boosting productivity and efficiency. Learning to Code fosters a growth mindset. It may feel like learning a foreign language, but with the benefit of instant feedback. No need to wait to go on leave and visit another country to practice your skills. Feedback arrives as soon as you hit Enter.

Coding can be a fun and social activity. As we head into the 21st century, many coding projects are collaborative. At NAVMAC and Millington, or any workplace, as more people pick up coding skills, User groups and enthusiasts share ideas, solve problems together, and making learning and working more fun and productive.

1.2 Who Codes?

Coding is not just for computer scientists, mathematicians, and engineers! By analogy:

  • You dont need to be a mechanical engineer to change your car oil.
  • You dont need to be a linguistic or etymologist to write a fun short story.
  • Gardening is not just for horticulturist, botanists, and professional landscape artists.
  • Cooking is not just for professional chefs and food critics.
  • Photography is accessible to everyone with a smart phone.
  • Fitness and sport is not just for professional athletes.

Coding is for everyone.

Learning to code, may open your mind up to new ways of thinking and expressing yourself. While coding certainly demands that one think critically, mathematically, and logically, it also asks one to think artistically and organizationally. NAVMAC professionals may find learning to code can dove tail well with learning about statistics, as in the attached lecture notes by the late Professor Spector. https://www.stat.berkeley.edu/~spector/s133/

We will touch on just the first two chapters today.

1.3 Why R?

In this document, we will use R, as our introduction to coding. Written by and for statisticians, R proves to be an immediately applicable language at NAVMAC, due to its ability to handle large and varied amounts of data. As an interpreted language you will see immediate feedback of commands.

R installs easily on NMCI machines and is freely available as an open source project, so one can practice using it both at work and at home. R continues to be developed and expanded, especially through packages, and also a mature language, with lots of tutorials and lessons found online.

2 Getting Started

2.1 Install Fest

R is available on multiple platforms. Click on each link for more information.

NMCI machines

Copy the following code to a text file, and save it has R_installer.bat. Run this file, and R will install on your machine.

REM New script to download and install R
REM slc October 7, 2024
REM uses winget instead of bitsadmin

winget download Rproject.R

REM Install R to R_folder. The foobaronetwo folder made
REM to temporarily change TMP / TEMP variables
md c:\foobaronetwo
md c:\r_folder
set tmp=c:\foobaronetwo
set temp=c:\foobaronetwo

c:

REM different for each user
cd c:\users\%username%\Downloads

REM change directory into that folder
set "target=Rproject"
for /D %%D in ("%target%*") do (
     cd "%%D"
     set "found=%%D"
     goto :found
)
echo Directory not found
goto :eof
:found
echo Directory found: %CD%
echo %found%
set "fullpath=c:\r_folder\%found%"

REM run installer
for %%i in (*.exe) do (
   start "" "%%i" /DIR="%fullpath%"
)

NVD

In NVD, you can run the installer directly, without indicating a folder off the c drive. The installer will default to a folder in the users profile, e.g. c:\Users\123456789.MIL\AppData\Local\Programs\R\R-4.4.2\

Download the installer from the CRAN or use winget package manager. Press Windows-X and select Windows Powershell. Type winget install Rproject.R

Package Managers

The secret sauce script to install R on NMCI machines is the Windows Package Manager called winget. Package managers are increasingly common on various operating systems. For example:

Linux Ubuntu users can run

sudo apt-get install r-base

FreeBSD users can run

sudo pkg install R

CRAN (Official site)

The Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) is the central software repository of R software supported by the R Foundation. You may download R and R packages from these CRAN sites.

Some CRAN mirrors include:

  • https://cran.r-project.org/
  • https://cran.rstudio.com
  • https://mirrors.ocf.berkeley.edu/cran/

Advana Edge

DoD offering of open source tools, including R, made available in an Amazon Web Services Cloud environment. After filling out and routing a SAAR form, you will have access to these offerings.

  • Advana Edge Onboarding Guide: https://wiki.advana.data.mil/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=125341926
  • Advana Edge email POC: cdao-advana-edge@groups.mail.mil
  • Advana Edge Portal: https://portal.ae.az.advana.data.mil/

WebR Project

WebR is a version of the statistical language R for the browser and Node.js using WebAssembly, via Emscripten. This means that R is being run completely within the users browser. Packages will be downloaded each time you begin a new session.

This project is still being developed, the API is changing, and in still an alpha stage. If you are having problems installing R, this is a quick and dirty way to learn the syntax. But dont use this for production work.

  • Documentation: https://docs.r-wasm.org/webr/latest/
  • https://webr.r-wasm.org/latest/

2.2 RStudio

RStudio provides a richer environment to use R. After installing R, visit https://posit.co/download/rstudio-desktop/ to obtain RStudio.

On an NMCI seat, RStudio can be downloaded via R, using NMCI Proxies with:

Sys.setenv(http_proxy="NMCIProxyB1:8080")
Sys.setenv(https_proxy="NMCIProxyB1Secure:8443")
options(timeout = 600) # minutes

folderDownload = r"(c:\TransHere)" 
dir.create(folderDownload)
myURL = "https:/"
myURL = paste(myURL, 
"download1.rstudio.org",
"electron",
"windows",
"RStudio-2024.12.0-467.zip",
sep = "/")

myLoc <- strsplit(myURL, "/")[[1]]
myLoc <- myLoc[ length(myLoc) ]
myLoc <- paste0(folderDownload,"\\",myLoc)

download.file(myURL, myLoc)

Once you have the zip file, (in the c:\TransHere folder), unzip the contents to a folder off the c: drive, c:\r_folder, for example.

3 General Programming Tools

This is a brief interlude as we download and install R, boot up your machine, and load up an R workspace. We can discuss more programming tools, but R and RStudio remain the main focus today.

RStudio allows users to handle more than just R coding. It can help users mix text and code in R, Python, Julia, shell scripts, SQL, JavaScript, \(\LaTeX{}\), and RMarkdown. This document is written in RMarkdown. RStudio is an example of an Integrated Development Environment.

3.1 Text Editors

Software development and code is written in text. Various text editors help the programmer make code in various languages. Output is rendered using a monospaced font, as placement of text on the page is not as important as the content and meaning of the commands.

There are dozen of text editors to choose from. Some common ones are:

  • Notepad.exe
    • Bundled with Windows since the 1980s
    • Largely unchanged until ~2022
    • New features: dark theme, spell check, web lookup, AI integration
  • Notepad++
    • Easy to use and feature full text editor
    • Standard software on NMCI DEV Seats since 2024
  • vi or vim
    • vi was originally written by Bill Joy in 1976 for the Unix operating systems
    • Guaranteed to be installed on any Unix-like operating system. (FreeBSD, Linux, etc.)
    • The de facto standard for Unix
    • Predates IBM CUA standards
  • emacs
    • Honorable mention due to Editor Wars of the 1990s

Common text editor features include:

  • Find and replace
  • Undo / Redo
  • Syntax Highlight
  • Line Numbering

3.2 IDEs

Integrated Development Environments like RStudio expand on text editors.

Examples of IDEs are:

  • RStudio
  • VS Code
    • See https://vscode.dev to instantly see this interface.
  • Spyder
  • PyCharm

In addition to Text Editor features, IDE add:

  • Code completion
  • Version Control
  • Instant Preview of Markup Languages
  • AI assistance (Co-pilot)

4 R: First Encounter

Our first goal in using a scripted language is to start a Read-Eval-Print-Loop (REPL). This is an interactive programming environment, where you may enter commands and immediately get results.

One may want to send more than just one command at a time to a programming language, and instead run an entire script. Using the text editor or IDE of choice, you can interactively build a script while testing out each lines as needed.

4.1 R as a calculator

1+3
## [1] 4
sin(10)
## [1] -0.5440211

4.4 Scripting

In Rgui.exe, clicking on File -> New Script, will open a new window in which one can write an entire sequence of commands. To run a line of code, just press Control-R when the cursor is on that line.

In R Studio, the script window is a special pane in which one can write a script. To run each line, press Control-Enter.

In either of these environments, one can also highlight several lines at once, and run those lines by either Control-R or Control-Enter.

We saw a short script in downloading RStudio, and below, you may cut and paste lines of code to reproduce the demonstrated code.

4.5 Comments

The # Symbol tells R that the remain bits of a line is a comment, and will not be run. Comments can help you and other follow your thinking and approach to problems. At first, comments might be notes to yourself as you learn a new syntax, but as you gain familiarity with a language, comments will end up describing why things are being done rather than just what is being done.

Some general advice for comments:

  • Keep in mind the audience for your code and comments.
  • Keep it Simple Dont over complicate. Write them in simple language, as if you are explaining the code to someone who isnt familiar with it.
  • Be Concise. Be brief and to the point. Avoid long paragraphs, focus on key insights.
  • Use Comments for Clarity. If a piece of code is complex or might confuse others (or even you in the future), add a comment to clarify.
  • Avoid Obvious Comments. For example i=i+1 doesnt need the comment #increase i by one.
  • Update Comments If code changes, remember to update the comments accordingly. Outdate comments can be worse than no comments at all.
  • Use TODO Comments if something isnt finished yet or needs improvement.

4.6 Packages

R is actively being developed. In addition to the base set of commands, you will want to additional packages. These can downloaded from the CRAN.

4.6.1 Installing Packages

Additional packages can be downloaded using the install.packages() command. From an NMCI seat, execute these lines before using install.packages():

Sys.setenv(http_proxy="NMCIProxyB1:8080")
Sys.setenv(https_proxy="NMCIProxyB1Secure:8443")

For example:

install.packages("beepr")

Alternatively, use the older method for downloading, and the RStudio servers:

options(download.file.method='wininet')
install.packages("beepr", repos = "https://cran.rstudio.com")

4.6.2 Using Packages

Once you have your packages downloaded, the library() command loads the package.

Lets explore the built in tcltk package comes built into R. Tcl/tk is an older method of building graphical user interfaces (GUIs), originating in the late 1980s, from UC Berkeley.

library(tcltk)
tk_messageBox(message= "hello world, hello NAVMAC")

Since we took some time to download the beepr package, we might want to demonstrate what it does, and how a for loop works in R.

library(beepr)
?beep
for (i in 1:11){
  beep(i)
  Sys.sleep(3) # pause for 3 seconds before sounds.
}

5 User Interfaces

5.1 Excel VBA

At NAVMAC, sometimes R is called from VBA. The attached Macro Enabled Spreadsheet, launch_R_viaExcel.xlsm, is an example of this. A few Code 50 products use this solution for end users.

5.2 As a batch script.

In Windows, we can use the Rscript.exe command to run some scripts. We can put this into a Windows batch file that the end user can run.

path c:\r_folder\R-4.4.2\bin\x64;%path%

Rscript yourfileHere.r

pause

5.3 UNIX scripting

In UNIX, a script can be made executable, if the path to the R interpreter is specified, in the first line. The combination of #! is sometimes called a shebang. The file can be made executable with a UNIX command chmod. For example, chmod +x myScript.r adds the executable property to a file. The file might read:

!#/usr/bin/Rscript
library(tcltk)
tk_messageBox(message="hi")

6 Base R

6.1 Functions

Users can make customized functions. For example, to convert temperature from Fahrenheit to Celsius, we use the formula: \[ C = \frac{5}{9}\left(F-32\right) \]

convTemp <- function(F){
  C = (5/9)*(F-32)
  return(C)
}

Now we can use this function:

convTemp(32) # Freezing of water
## [1] 0
convTemp(77) # Standard laboratory temperature
## [1] 25
convTemp(68) #
## [1] 20

6.2 Programming Control

Earlier we saw a for loop with the beepr package. A while loop can accomplish the same thing:

i = 1
while (i <= 11){
  beep(i)
  Sys.sleep(3)
  i = i + 1
}

We can use the previously defined convTemp function to list a series of common temperatures:

F = 32
while (F <=122){
  C = convTemp(F)
  myString = paste(F,"degrees F is", C, "degrees Celsius.")
  print(myString)
  F = F + 9
}
## [1] "32 degrees F is 0 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "41 degrees F is 5 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "50 degrees F is 10 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "59 degrees F is 15 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "68 degrees F is 20 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "77 degrees F is 25 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "86 degrees F is 30 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "95 degrees F is 35 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "104 degrees F is 40 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "113 degrees F is 45 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "122 degrees F is 50 degrees Celsius."

Finally, we will introduce the if statement. We can modify the loop above, to make comments about the temperature.

F = 32
while (F <=122){
  C = convTemp(F)
  myString = paste(F,"degrees F is", C, "degrees Celsius.")
  if (F > 90){
       myString = paste(myString, "That's way too hot!!")
     }
  print(myString)
  F = F + 9
}
## [1] "32 degrees F is 0 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "41 degrees F is 5 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "50 degrees F is 10 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "59 degrees F is 15 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "68 degrees F is 20 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "77 degrees F is 25 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "86 degrees F is 30 degrees Celsius."
## [1] "95 degrees F is 35 degrees Celsius. That's way too hot!!"
## [1] "104 degrees F is 40 degrees Celsius. That's way too hot!!"
## [1] "113 degrees F is 45 degrees Celsius. That's way too hot!!"
## [1] "122 degrees F is 50 degrees Celsius. That's way too hot!!"

6.3 Vectors and Data Frames

for/while loops, if/else if/else statements are standard constructs in all programming languages. R is a vectorized language, with syntax that can handle operations without using loops. Not only does this simplify notation, R will handle these operations faster!

Vectors handle only one mode of data. (Numeric, boolean, strings, Dates, etc). A data frame is an object in R, which is like a rectangular array of data.

6.3.2 Data Frames

Lets make a data frame for temperatures:

myDF = data.frame( degreeF = 0:212)
myDF$degreeC = (5/9)*(myDF$degreeF - 32)

Data frames can columns are vectors. Vectors do not need to be just numerical data:

myDF$Comment = "This is a temperature"

Lets modify the Comment column to say that it is too hot if \(F>90\) and too cold if \(F < 50\).

t1 = myDF$degreeF > 90
myDF[t1,c("degreeF","degreeC")] # to print out the items of interest to illustrate

Finally, suppose one finds fractional degrees confusing. The degreeF column is already just the integers between 0 and 212. Lets filter out for integer values of degreeC.

t3 = myDF$degreeC == floor(myDF$degreeC)
myDF = myDF[t3,]
datatable(myDF, rownames=FALSE)

library(networkD3)
data(MisLinks)
data(MisNodes)
# Create graph
forceNetwork(Links = MisLinks, Nodes = MisNodes, Source = "source",
             Target = "target", Value = "value", NodeID = "name",
             Group = "group", opacity = 0.9, zoom = TRUE)
